Dow30<-read.csv('Dow.csv', stringsAsFactors = FALSE,sep = ",") #read the file
Dow30$Closing.Values<- sub(",","", Dow30$Closing.Values) #get rid of NAs
Dow30$Closing.Values<-as.numeric(Dow30$Closing.Values)#Transform everything to Numeric for next step
#get the returns
Dow30$Return <- (diff(Dow30$Closing.Values) / lag(Dow30$Closing.Values, k = 1))*100
## Warning in diff(Dow30$Closing.Values)/lag(Dow30$Closing.Values, k = 1): longer
## object length is not a multiple of shorter object length
Average_return<-mean(Dow30$Return, na.rm = TRUE)



cat("The Average Dow Return is:",Average_return)#cat function to print writhing and variable together
## The Average Dow Return is: 0.6882175
#b
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = Dow30, aes(x = Return)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, color = 'black', fill = 'lightblue') +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Returns", x = "Returns", y = "Frequency")

print("It is normally distributed")
## [1] "It is normally distributed"
#c
sd_return <- sd(Dow30$Return, na.rm = TRUE)
sd_return
## [1] 4.134843
cat("The std dev of proportion of defective components is:",sd_return)
## The std dev of proportion of defective components is: 4.134843
TotalSampleSize <- length(Dow30$Return)
#Find the Mean
mean_prop<-mean(Dow30$Return, na.rm = TRUE)
## One std dev bounds
One_SD_Range_Lower <- mean_prop - 1*sd_return
One_SD_Range_Upper <- mean_prop + 1*sd_return


## Proportion of observations within 1 SD (should be around 68%) 
Num_Within_One_SD <- length(which(Dow30$Return >= One_SD_Range_Lower & Dow30$Return <= One_SD_Range_Upper))
Percent_Within_One_SD <- 100*(Num_Within_One_SD/TotalSampleSize)
Percent_Within_One_SD
## [1] 72.32558
## Two std dev bounds
Two_SD_Range_Lower <- mean_prop - 2*sd_return
Two_SD_Range_Upper <- mean_prop + 2*sd_return

## Proportion of observations within 2 SD (should be around 95%) 
Num_Within_Two_SD <- length(which(Dow30$Return >= Two_SD_Range_Lower & Dow30$Return <= Two_SD_Range_Upper))
Percent_Within_Two_SD <- 100*(Num_Within_Two_SD/TotalSampleSize)
Percent_Within_Two_SD
## [1] 95.34884
## Three std dev bounds
Three_SD_Range_Lower <- mean_prop - 3*sd_return
Three_SD_Range_Upper <- mean_prop + 3*sd_return

## Proportion of observations within 2 SD (should be around 99.7%) 
Num_Within_Three_SD <- length(which(Dow30$Return >= Three_SD_Range_Lower & Dow30$Return <= Three_SD_Range_Upper))
Percent_Within_Three_SD <- 100*(Num_Within_Three_SD/TotalSampleSize)

cat(Percent_Within_One_SD,"percent of returns are within 1SD from the mean")
## 72.32558 percent of returns are within 1SD from the mean
cat(Percent_Within_Two_SD,"percent of returns are within 2SD from the mean")
## 95.34884 percent of returns are within 2SD from the mean
cat(Percent_Within_Three_SD,"percent of returns are within 3SD from the mean")
## 98.83721 percent of returns are within 3SD from the mean

print("The first quartile (Q1) is the value below which 25% of the data falls. It marks the lower edge of the box in the boxplot.")
## [1] "The first quartile (Q1) is the value below which 25% of the data falls. It marks the lower edge of the box in the boxplot."
print("The median (Q2) is the value that divides the data into two halves, with 50% of the data falling below it and 50% above it. It is represented by the line inside the box.")
## [1] "The median (Q2) is the value that divides the data into two halves, with 50% of the data falling below it and 50% above it. It is represented by the line inside the box."
print("The third quartile (Q3) is the value below which 75% of the data falls. It marks the upper edge of the box in the boxplot.")
## [1] "The third quartile (Q3) is the value below which 75% of the data falls. It marks the upper edge of the box in the boxplot."
#e
## Compute quartiles
Q1 <- quantile(Dow30$Return, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE) ## First quartile
Q2 <- quantile(Dow30$Return, 0.50, na.rm = TRUE) ## Second quartile
Q3 <- quantile(Dow30$Return, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE) ## Third quartile
IQR <- IQR(Dow30$Return, na.rm = TRUE) ## IQR
### Identify outliers
outliervector <- with(Dow30, 
                      Dow30$Outlier <- ifelse(Dow30$Return >= Q3 + 1.5*IQR, 
                                                 "Yes", "No"))
Dow30["Outlier"] <- outliervector
extremeoutliervector <- with(Dow30, 
                             Dow30$Outlier <- ifelse(Dow30$Return >= Q3+ 3*IQR, 
                                                        "Yes", "No"))
Dow30["ExtremeOutlier"] <- extremeoutliervector

# Sort the DataFrame to display outliers first
Dow30 <- Dow30[order(Dow30$Outlier, Dow30$ExtremeOutlier, decreasing = TRUE), ]

p<-0.27
cost_per <- 500
cost_new_machine <- 7500
budget<- 2000

#calculate probability of fixing machine within budget

fix_prob<-c() # Probability of fixing the machine within n_max visits

n_max <- floor(budget / cost_per)
fix_prob <- numeric(n_max)
for (n in 1:n_max) {
  fix_prob[n] <- choose(n - 1, 0) * p^1 * (1 - p)^(n - 1)
}

cat("The probabilities that 1-4 visits are needed for fixing the machine are:",fix_prob)
## The probabilities that 1-4 visits are needed for fixing the machine are: 0.27 0.1971 0.143883 0.1050346
#b

expected_number<-sum(1:n_max * fix_prob) #but in reality, number of services is usually an integer

cat("The expected number of services needed to fix the machine will be",expected_number)
## The expected number of services needed to fix the machine will be 1.515987
#c
#Expected amount spent on the machine
replacement_prob<-(1-p)^4 # the possibility that the machine is still not fixed after 4th service, then we have to replace it

expected_amount_spent<- sum((expected_number*cost_per*fix_prob))+replacement_prob*7500
cat("The expected amount spent on the machine will be:$",expected_amount_spent)
## The expected amount spent on the machine will be:$ 2672.605

#b
# Function for calculating the expected profit vector
calculate_expected_profit <- function(demand_values, demand_probs, production_values, production_cost) {
  expected_profits <- numeric(length(production_values))
  for (i in 1:length(production_values)) {
    production <- production_values[i]
    expected_profits[i] <- sum((pmin(demand_values, production) * 9 - 
                                  production * production_cost - fixed_cost_each) * demand_probs)
  }
  return(expected_profits)
}
#use the created function to calculate the expected profits for each type of pizza
expected_profits_plain<- calculate_expected_profit(plain_demand, plain_possibility, productions, cost_per_plain)
